I"O.<p>As the bus bounced and jolted into the sixth hour of the ride, I thought to myself: wow, the mountains are beautiful. The winding switchbacks, the scattered corrugated rooftops, and the infinite levels of terrace farms filled my vision. The bus trudged past slope after slope of myriad greens, from the yellowish rice paddies and wheat fields to the shadowy rhododendron and oak trees. The road had long before lost its paving and was reduced to a layer of dust over rocks, its width barely enough to fit two buses side-by-side with maybe six inches of wiggle room—we slowed many times to accommodate oncoming vehicles, many of which came so close that I could have leaned out the window and given the driver in the other car an encouraging pat on the shoulder.</p>

<p>When I saw the real mountains, fitted with powdery white caps and scraggly tree lines, I was breathless. The first peek I got was over a sharp bump in the road, and it was so ephemeral I couldn’t really believe it until we saw the mountains again, and again, and again. Priyankar reminded me that the “mountains” covered in farming were just hills, the usual ones at the bottom of the Himalayas that rise up 2,500 meters above sea level, unlike the mountains which can break 8,000 meters. In LA we too have “mountains,” the kind that you can climb in two hours if you are feeling fit, four if you are taking a stroll. Farther away we have Mount Whitney, which joins the few and far between “fourteeners” (the peak being taller than 14,000 feet, or 4267 meters). The true mountains, as designated by those familiar with the Himalayas, are the ones that have shed all vegetation at the top, the ones that have a cover of perennial snow. Here in Nepal, as a rough estimate, you need to surpass 5000 meters to truly experience a mountain. I made a mental note.</p>

<p>At the end of our eight-hour bus ride, we took refuge in a local hostel as the next stop was too far to hike to that day. This lifestyle is typical on common trekking routes, where there are many villages and lone hostels along the way. At Syafrubesi (1500 m), where we started, nearly every building on the main road was a hostel. Trekkers seemed to outnumber the locals, and you could really tell because every trekker was white and European.</p>

<p>Priyankar and I had debated whether or not to pay for a guide. Mostly, we were weighing the literal cost of $20 a day versus the benefit of navigating a region hit hard by the 2015 earthquake, and we decided that the gift of knowledge was worth more than money. I am thankful for this decision since our guide, Pemba, was actually a local to the Langtang region, so familiar with it that he would literally pick fruits off of wild trees for us to try (dogwood or sea buckthorn, anyone??). He was also well-acclimated to trekking and exercise, so much that he carried my bag for the first three days of the trek.</p>

<p>Note: I had overpacked. Guilty. I really tried to not overpack, but I still did. I think this is a standard first-trek experience. When we loaded onto the bus, I lifted my bag up and the bus guy exclaimed out loud at how heavy it was. On the first day of trekking, I got so sweaty and tired that Pemba suggested we switch bags; I refused on the grounds of pride, but after he asked maybe three or four times I capitulated. I literally felt like a weight had come off my back. My bag was about 10 kg, while his bag was maybe 2 kg at most. He said that all he had was a toothbrush! (A slight exaggeration… he also had water, sunglasses, and a light jacket.)</p>

<p>A good chunk of the trekking experience for me was the feeling of being on a never-ending hike, the sensation of my legs being tired and my lungs feeling worn with no respite in sight. But that was far outweighed by the scenery we saw. The first day, we climbed 900 meters from broad-leaf deciduous forest into slightly less broad-leaf deciduous forest. The second day was another 1100 meters into alpine scrub and grassland at an elevation of about 3500 meters. The third day we hiked a bit more into pure alpine grassland at 3850 meters. All of this was with the hills and mountains in the backdrop. I could go on for hours about how beautiful the mountains are; instead, I will let the pictures (next email) speak for themselves.</p>

<p>On the fourth day, we set out around 7:00 to climb Tsergo Ri, a peak that was listed on the map as being 4984 m tall. The easiest part of this hike was that we went with small daypacks instead of our full-size bags. The hardest part was the thin air, the feeling of constantly gasping, like someone is sucking the oxygen just out of your body’s reach. I think we budgeted three hours to summit, but it took us four and a half. We crossed the tree line and into areas with remnants of snow. When we arrived at the top, we looked around to see mountains in every direction in their full sunlit glory. Later, looking at multiple references, I discovered that Tsergo Ri is frequently listed as being anywhere between 4900 and 5100 meters tall. Did we “truly experience the mountains?”</p>

<p>Unclear, though being in the mountains for several days certainly provides one with a sense of perspective. Several sections of the trekking trail were built over rock debris left behind by landslides, some of which were caused by the 2015 earthquake. As we crossed the largest debris section, several hundred meters long, we looked at the cliff where the gashes in the mountain still shone bright like fresh wounds. Priyankar reminded me that the earthquake generated a landslide and avalanche that destroyed the entire village of Langtang. Over three years, the fallen ice has melted but the rocks still remain. We could still see the trees across the valley that were knocked over by the avalanche-generated winds. The new village of Langtang has been built upriver of the landslide, but the old village is still buried under the earth. Walking over the landslides and days later to the top of Tsergo Ri, I felt witness to the mountains in all of their imposing grandeur, their immensity flirting with the caprice of nature.</p>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4000/photos/travel_nepal_tsergori.jpg" alt="Tsergo Ri" /></p>

<p>As we climbed down from Tsergo Ri, I stumbled over every patch of dirt and gravel, my knees feeling weak. Sitting on a boulder for a momentary gasp of air, I noticed someone farther down the trail, his nearly imperceptible silhouette framed by vast expanses of rock. I will never forget how small he and I both were.</p>

<hr />

<p>On our way down from Langtang Valley, Pemba brought us on a two-day detour to his village. We climbed from our final hostel up the hill, down the other side, and then up another hill, finally arriving at Badjung. I should say here that I tried to double check the spelling of the village name through the internet, but there are no results on either Wikipedia or Google Maps. On the way he explained to me that his village had about seventy families, totaling to about four hundred folks. The size of the village was rather evident when Pemba began to converse with every person we passed by. I was amazed that he knew everyone who lived in his area. Of course, if you live in a community similarly small in which everyone works as a subsistence farmer, then you all go through the best and worst of times together, like one large family. In Badjung we met his sister and his mother along with a few other of his relatives. I didn’t really understand much of what was said that evening because of the language barrier, but it was easy to see how close everyone was with each other.</p>

<p>The mountain village life is really different from the city, and I daresay it is somewhat distinct from a village in the plains. The distance between places is compounded by the ever-present factor of elevation. Every time you move, you go either uphill or downhill, including: walking to school, going to the nearest town (Syafrubesi), visiting a friend, and doing farmwork. As mentioned earlier, the hillsides are covered in terrace farms. How people (and their legs) manage this constant labor up and down the hill is a little beyond me. For the children, school in the village goes up to third grade. But after that, they have to walk over to the neighboring village on the opposite hill—which means going all the way down the hill, crossing the river (or walking to the bridge), then going up the other hill. For a child, I would say this might take two hours if one kept the fastest pace they could, three hours at a stroll, and add at least half an hour if you are carrying a bag.</p>

<p>Across our many hikes, Pemba shared with me that he wants to start a good school in his village. He told me with frustration that someone from the village had gone into politics saying they’d put the village first, but that this person only helped their own family. He told me that he works as a guide among other jobs because he wants to help the village, and he has a long way to go before he raises enough money for a school. I asked him if he wants to teach, or if he wants to be in charge of the school. He responded that he just wants the school to exist, because education will help the village improve. Among his goals is one day moving to America to work and then send money home. But he also says that sometimes he is tired of dreaming, and sometimes he thinks he should just keep on farming with his family like everyone else.</p>

<p>We had a lot of trouble communicating because his English, while infinitely better than my rudimentary Nepali, is still somewhat basic. But I was glad to understand these parts I share with you. As we left Badjung our final morning, Pemba gave both me and Priyankar a firm hug. Making full eye contact with me, he spoke firmly: “Don’t forget me. Don’t forget this village.” Those words stuck with me as we ran down the hill to catch the bus back to Kathmandu, and nine hours later, we arrived at Priyankar’s house with the mountains, the valleys, and their people fresh in our memories.</p>

<p>Other notes:
1) Pri and I decided I should extend my stay by about ten days so I can catch another set of festivities during Tihar, which is the Nepali Hindu festival of lights (like Diwali in India, also at the same time). My new flight to Kunming (China) is November 12th. Now that we have done a trek in Nepal, I feel empowered, and I may go trekking for a little through parts of China—I am especially excited about trekking to Tiger Leaping Gorge and Lake Lugu, both in the Yunnan region. Let me know if you have advice and/or recommendations. I have been told that winter is coming (thanks Ned Stark), so I am a little antsy for this reason, but I will play it by ear…</p>

<p>2) Some of you may know I am into BIRDS… actually I bought a bird guide for Nepal in one of the bookstores here, and we brought it on the trek. We saw and heard a whole lot of animals. A short listing here, for those who care: Bearded Vultures, a Long-tailed Minivet, Spotted Nutcrackers, a Brown-fronted Woodpecker, a Blue-fronted Redstart (lol), a strangely flock-like group of Variegated Laughingthrushes, multiple flocks of Snow Pigeons, Red-billed Choughs (Pemba says they’re edible), Alpine Choughs, musk deer, a couple lizards, and a monkey. Things we did not see: Himalayan Monals (national bird of Nepal), snow leopards.</p>

